## Q10: What is the risk of using kill -9 (SIGKILL) right away on a production database or application?
"Sending a `SIGKILL` instantly terminates a process at the kernel level without giving it a chance to handle the signal. The application cannot execute any cleanup routines, leaving file descriptors open, network connections abruptly severed, and data half-written. In a database, this can cause transaction corruption and force a lengthy crash-recovery process upon reboot. Always try a graceful `SIGTERM` (kill) first."
